'''Operation Leader''' was a successful air attack conducted by the [[United States Navy]] against German shipping in the vicinity of [[Bodø]], Norway, on 4 October 1943, during [[World War II]]. The raid was executed by aircraft flying from the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Ranger|CV-4|6}}, which at the time was attached to the British [[Home Fleet]]. The American airmen located many German and Norwegian ships in this area, and are believed to have destroyed five and damaged another seven. Two German aircraft searching for the Allied fleet were shot down as well. Three American aircraft were destroyed in combat during the operation, and another crashed while landing.

The attack followed a two-year lull in Allied aircraft carrier operations against Norway, and took the German forces by surprise. The choice of the target area was guided by intelligence gained from decoding German radio signals and reports from Norwegian [[Secret Intelligence Service]] agents, and two Norwegian airmen flew with the attack force to provide advice on the local geography. While historians have found it difficult to determine the exact number of ships sunk, Operation Leader damaged the German war effort by considerably disrupting the [[convoy]] system in the region and reducing shipments of iron ore.

==Background==

During mid- to late-1943 the [[Home Fleet]], the [[Royal Navy]]'s main striking force stationed in the United Kingdom, was augmented by two forces of [[United States Navy]] warships to replace British ships dispatched to the Mediterranean and Pacific. These reinforcements were considered necessary to ensure that the fleet remained able to counter the German battle group based in Norway, which was built around the [[battleship]]s [[German battleship Tirpitz|''Tirpitz'']] and [[German battleship Scharnhorst|''Scharnhorst'']], and the [[heavy cruiser]] [[German cruiser Deutschland|''Lützow'']].{{sfn|Roskill|1960|pp=57–58}}

The initial US Navy [[task force]] arrived in May, and comprised the battleships {{USS|Alabama|BB-60|6}} and {{USS|South Dakota|BB-57|2}}, the heavy cruiser {{USS|Tuscaloosa|CA-37|6}} and five [[destroyer]]s. This force came under the command of Rear Admiral [[Olaf M. Hustvedt]] and conducted patrols into the [[Norwegian Sea]] with British warships, but did not make contact with German forces. The two battleships and the destroyers were withdrawn in August, and proceeded to the Pacific.{{sfn|Morison|2001|pp=229–230}}{{sfn|Roskill|1960|p=58}}

A second task force built around the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Ranger|CV-4|6}} replaced the two battleships in September 1943. The other elements of this force were the heavy cruisers {{USS|Augusta|CA-31|6}} and ''Tuscaloosa'', as well as five destroyers; Hustvedt remained in command.{{sfn|Roskill|1960|pp=58, 72}}{{sfn|Morison|2001|pp=231–232}} ''Ranger''{{'}}s [[Wing (military aviation unit)|air wing]] was made up of three [[Squadron (aviation)|squadrons]]: [[VF-41]] with 27 [[Grumman F4F Wildcat]] [[Fighter aircraft|fighters]], [[VFA-14 (U.S. Navy)|VB-41]] with 27 [[Douglas SBD Dauntless]] [[dive bomber]]s, and [[Sea Control Squadron 21|VT-41]] with 18 [[Grumman TBF Avenger]] [[torpedo bomber]]s.{{sfn|Brown|2009|p=22}} Prior to ''Ranger''{{'}}s arrival the Home Fleet was assigned only a single aircraft carrier, the elderly {{HMS|Furious|47|6}}, which was unavailable for operations at the time as she was undergoing a refit.{{sfn|Roskill|1960|p=58}} ''Ranger'' had last seen combat against [[Vichy France|Vichy French]] forces while supporting the [[Operation Torch]] landings in Morocco during November 1942, and had later been used to ferry aircraft to North Africa and train aircrews off the United States east coast.<ref name="Ranger DANFS" /> On 8 September 1943 the main body of the Home Fleet, including the American task force, sortied in response to reports that ''Tirpitz'', ''Scharnhorst'' and nine destroyers had put to sea. The Allied force returned to the Home Fleet's main base at [[Scapa Flow]] the next day after it was learned that the German ships had returned to port after [[Operation Zitronella|briefly attacking]] Allied positions on [[Svalbard|Spitsbergen]].{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=192}}

On 22 September the German battle group in Norway [[Operation Source|was attacked]] by several British [[midget submarine]]s. This raid inflicted significant damage on ''Tirpitz'', leaving the battleship unable to proceed to sea until repairs were complete. Once this was known to the Allies, the commander of the Home Fleet, Admiral [[Bruce Fraser, 1st Baron Fraser of North Cape|Bruce Fraser]], judged that the changed balance of forces would allow his force to assume a more offensive role by attacking German shipping off Norway and restarting the [[Arctic Convoys]] to the [[Soviet Union]].{{sfn|Roskill|1960|p=69}}

==Preparations==

Following the midget submarine operation Fraser decided to dispatch the main body of the Home Fleet to conduct an air attack against ports and German shipping in northern Norway. ''Ranger'' was assigned responsibility for attacking the port of [[Bodø]], which was an important rendezvous point for German and German-controlled Norwegian shipping.{{#tag:ref|By the start of World War II, Norway had the world's fourth largest merchant navy. Following the [[Norwegian Campaign|German conquest of Norway]] in 1940, some 15 percent of the total tonnage of the Norwegian merchant navy was caught up in German-held territories. Those ships sailed in occupied Norway and between Norway and other German-occupied countries, exporting Norwegian products and bringing supplies back to Norway. On the Norwegian coast the Norwegian merchant ships brought supplies and passengers to coastal communities. Many of the vessels were confiscated by the Germans, and others forced to carry German troops and military supplies, making them targets for the Allied war effort. During the war years 237 Norwegian ships in occupied territories were lost, along with 1,071 people.{{sfn|Thowsen|1995a|p=157}}{{sfn|Thowsen|1995b|p=175}}|group=Note}} Fraser also initially planned to use the aircraft carrier {{HMS|Formidable|67|6}} to attack shipping in the port of [[Brønnøysund]],{{sfn|Melien|2002|p=29}} to the south of Bodø, but this element of the operation was cancelled due to unfavourable weather.{{sfn|Morison|2001|pp=231–232}}{{sfn|Roskill|1960|p=102}} The slow-moving [[Fairey Albacore]]s on ''Formidable'' required cloud cover to operate over hostile territory.{{sfn|Melien|2002|p=29}} While several ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' (German Air Force) bases were located near Bodø, most of the aircraft previously stationed in northern Norway had been transferred elsewhere and those that remained posed little threat to the Allied fleet.{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=232}} In the case no shipping could be found, the American pilots were given as alternative targets [[Bodø Main Air Station|Bodø Air Station]], the oil depot in Bodø, and radar installations at [[Røst]].{{sfn|Melien|2002|p=29}}

The Home Fleet's plans were informed by considerable intelligence on German shipping movements and forces in northern Norway. The Royal Navy's [[Operational Intelligence Centre]] collated information on these topics, and regularly provided assessments to the Home Fleet and other commands. The decision to attack the Bodø area was made on the basis of [[Ultra]] intelligence obtained by decoding German radio signals, from which the Allies learned that the ships in the region included the large [[oil tanker]] {{ship|German tanker|Schleswig||2}}, which was carrying fuel for the German battle group at [[Altafjord]].{{sfn|Hinsley|1984|p=282}} In addition, at the time of Operation Leader two groups of Norwegian [[Secret Intelligence Service]] (SIS) agents operated radio transmitters on the coast of [[Helgeland]]: "Crux III" on the island of [[Renga, Nordland|Renga]] and "Pisces" on [[Lurøya, Nordland|Lurøy]].{{#tag:ref|During World War II, the British [[Secret Intelligence Service]] cooperated with exiled Norwegian authorities in dispatching more than 100 radio transmitters with Norwegian operators to German-occupied Norway. The first transmitter became operational on 10 June 1940, the same day [[Norwegian Campaign|regular fighting]] ceased in Norway. Almost exclusively situated along the coast, the SIS agents primarily reported on shipping movements. In all, some 200 Norwegian SIS agents operated clandestinely in occupied Norway, supported by around 2,000 local helpers. Of the people involved, 26 agents and at least 9 locals lost their lives, either by being killed in action with German troops, being executed, or dying as a consequence of captivity.{{sfn|Nøkleby|1995|pp=371–373}}|group=Note}} Both groups provided reports to the Allies on the weather and shipping movements in the target area in the lead-up to the attack. From 3 October onwards, "Crux III" radioed weather reports every half hour.{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=197}}{{sfn|Ulstein|1990|pp=263–265}}

==Attack==

The Home Fleet sailed from Scapa Flow on 2 October 1943. The British elements of the force were the battleships {{HMS|Duke of York|17|6}} (Fraser's [[flagship]]) and {{HMS|Anson|79|2}}, the [[light cruiser]] {{HMS|Belfast| C35|6}} and seven destroyers. The US Navy component comprised ''Ranger'', ''Tuscaloosa'' and four destroyers.{{sfn|Morison|2001|pp=231–232}}{{sfn|Faulkner|2012|p=198}} The Allied ships were not detected by German forces during their voyage north, and arrived at the flying-off position for ''Ranger''{{'}}s air wing approximately {{convert|140|mi|km}} off Bodø shortly before dawn on 4 October.{{sfn|Roskill|1960|p=102}}{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=232}}
[[File:US Navy aircraft attack on German shipping in Bodo Harbor on 4 October 1943.jpeg|thumb|alt=Black and white aerial photo of two ships sailing together near the shoreline. One of the ships is partially obscured by a large splash.|left|The tanker ''Schleswig'' and the minesweeper ''M 365'' under attack]]

The US Navy attack force was organised into two groups of aircraft: the Northern Attack Group, which was to strike shipping at Bodø, and the Southern Attack Group, which was to target ships near the town of [[Sandnessjøen]] nearly {{convert|100|mi|km}} to the south.{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=193}} Both groups had one Norwegian navigator from [[No. 333 Squadron RAF]] in the lead aircraft, providing knowledge of the local geography.{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=198}}

The Northern Attack Group, which comprised 20 Dauntless dive bombers escorted by eight Wildcat fighters, began to take off at 6:18 am. These aircraft flew at low altitude towards Bodø until their crews sighted [[Myken Lighthouse]], and then turned to the north and climbed as they neared the target area.{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=232}} Weather conditions were clear, and the air crews had good visibility.{{sfn|Faulkner|2012|p=198}} Four Dauntlesses and a pair of Wildcats were detached from the force shortly after it passed Myken Lighthouse to search for German shipping near [[Åmnøya]] island. They soon sighted the {{GRT|8,000}} German freighter {{SS|La Plata|1922|2}}, and two of the dive bombers attacked the ship. The Americans believed that ''La Plata'' was badly damaged, and the six aircraft rejoined the main body of the Northern Attack Group.{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=232}}{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=197}}{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=193}}

In the meantime the other American aircraft continued north, sighting but not attacking many small cargo ships and fishing boats. At 7:30 am they located a German convoy comprising the steamer {{SS|Kerkplein||2}} and the tanker ''Schleswig'' under the escort of the [[minesweeper]] {{ship|German minesweeper|M 365||2}}. Eight of the Dauntlesses attacked ''Schleswig'' and another pair targeted ''Kerkplein'', inflicting significant damage on both. One of the escorting Wildcats was damaged by gunfire during the attack and returned to ''Ranger''.{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=232}}{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=194}} ''Schleswig'' was [[Beaching (nautical)|beached]] to avoid sinking, and later [[Marine salvage|salvaged]] and brought to Bodø for repairs.{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=197}} Following this engagement, the eight Dauntlesses which had yet to drop their bombs continued on to Bodø where they attacked four small German cargo ships: the {{GRT|2,719|link=off}} [[ore carrier]] {{SS|Rabat|1929|2}} was sunk, {{SS|Cap Guir||2}} was badly damaged, {{SS|Malaga|1935|2}} received minor damage from a near miss, and the small steamer {{SS|Ibis|1920|2}} was machine-gunned.{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=198}}{{sfn|Stern|2012|pp=194–195}} Two of the dive bombers were shot down by [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft guns]] located on the shore and ships. The crew of one of the aircraft survived and were taken prisoner after ditching into the sea, but both men on the other Dauntless were killed.{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=232}}{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=195}}
[[File:German freighter La Plata being attacked off Bodø in October 1944.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Black and white aerial photo of a merchant ship with splashes in the water along her port side. A monoplane aircraft is flying just above the ship.|The freighter ''La Plata'' being strafed by Wildcat fighters]]

The Southern Attack Group began launching from ''Ranger'' at 7:08 am. It was made up of ten Avenger torpedo bombers and six Wildcats.{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=232}} Two of the Avengers attacked the {{GRT|4,991|link=off}} Norwegian cargo ship {{MS|Topeka|1925|2}} off the island of [[Løkta]] south of Sandnessjøen; the ship was set on fire and beached to avoid sinking. Three of the Norwegian crew members on ''Topeka'' were killed in the attack, along with several German soldiers manning anti-aircraft guns on board the ship. One of the attacking aircraft was shot down by anti-aircraft fire from the shore with only its pilot,Lt(jg) John H. Palmer, surviving.{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=198}}{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=195}} ''Topeka'' was carrying a cargo of cement and timber, and had until the previous evening been sailing in an escorted German convoy. Local fishermen made their way to the burning vessel to help rescue those on board.{{sfn|Nordanger|1975|pp=86–87}}

Following the attack on ''Topeka'' the American aircraft continued north, and bombed and sank the {{GRT|687|link=off}} Norwegian [[cargo liner]] {{SS|Vaagan||2}} off [[Fagervika]] without loss of life.{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=198}}{{sfn|Sjøfartskontoret|1949|p=12}} The crew of ''Vaagan'' had observed the bombing of ''Topeka'' and brought their unarmed ship close to shore, lowering the [[Lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboats]] in preparation for a possible attack. ''Vaagan'' was carrying a cargo mostly of food for civilian consumption, and the sinking led to a [[margarine]] shortage in parts of northern Norway.{{sfn|Nordanger|1975|p=87}}{{#tag:ref|Following the sinking of several coastal steamers from 1941 onwards, the exiled Norwegian authorities lobbied the Allies to not attack Norwegian coastal shipping. This eventually led to an agreement in 1943 whereby British authorities issued instructions for pilots not to attack unescorted ships smaller than {{GRT|1,500}} on the coast of Norway. In several cases these instructions failed to prevent attacks on small Norwegian coasters.{{sfn|Nilsen|Thowsen|1990|pp=102–104}}{{sfn|Pettersen|1992|pp=179–182}} Before striking ''Vaagan'' the American aircraft observed and avoided attacking numerous Norwegian fishing vessels.{{sfn|Melien|2002|p=30}}|group=Note}} The force then bombed ''La Plata'', causing her to be beached on the island [[Rødøya]] where the ammunition on board exploded, and she burned for several days.{{sfn|Christensen|1988|pp=138–139}} The aircraft also bombed the {{GRT|4,300|link=off}} [[Kriegsmarine]] [[troop ship]] {{MS|Skramstad|1925|2}} (a Norwegian cargo ship requisitioned with her crew by the [[German occupation of Norway|German occupying authorities]]), which had some 850 German soldiers embarked and was protected by two escorts. ''Skramstad'' was severely damaged and beached, burning for days. The number of casualties on board this ship are unclear, with some sources stating that 200 of the troops died while others report that only one Norwegian sailor and a few German soldiers were killed. The [[Norwegian resistance movement]] claimed after the attack that around 360 Germans had been killed in the bombing of ''Skramstad'', while the official German reports state that 37 soldiers died.{{sfn|Christensen|1988|pp=138–139}}{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=199}} The American aircraft also [[strafing|strafed]] the German cargo ship {{SS|Wolsum||2}} and attacked the ammunition [[barge]] ''F231'', which was hit by a bomb and beached.{{sfn|Thomas|2010|p=27}} After all the aircraft had completed their attacks, the force returned to ''Ranger'' shortly before 9:00 am.{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=195}}{{sfn|Morison|2001|pp=232–233}} As well as the four American aircraft destroyed, six suffered damage from anti-aircraft artillery.{{sfn|Thomas|2010|pp=23–25}}

The German response to the raid was hampered by a shortage of capacity within the local military communication network. Following the attacks, a German report described their channels of communications as "constantly noisy with interruptions" during the attack. This prevented the Germans from sending warnings once the attack had begun.{{sfn|Thomas|2010|pp=25–27}}

==Aftermath==
[[File:Memorial to the pilots from USS Ranger in Fagervika - small version.jpg|thumb|alt=Color photo of two memorials made from stone located next to each other|A memorial (left) for the American pilots killed during Operation Leader, next to a memorial to Norwegian war dead from the [[Nesna]] area]]
At about 2 pm on 4 October, as the Home Fleet was sailing westwards, three German reconnaissance aircraft approached ''Ranger''. At this time two pairs of Wildcats were providing a [[combat air patrol]] over the fleet, and were guided to intercept the German aircraft by ''Ranger''{{'}}s fighter director. Two of the fighters shot down a [[Junkers Ju 88]] [[bomber]] {{convert|22|mi|km}} from the carrier, and the other pair downed a [[Heinkel He 115]] [[Floatplane|float plane]] {{convert|13|mi|km}} from ''Ranger''. The remaining aircraft, a Ju 88, was not sighted by the fighter pilots and managed to escape. These were the first German aircraft to have been shot down by US Navy aircraft. One of the Wildcats involved in this engagement crashed during landing, but its pilot survived.{{sfn|Stern|2012|p=195}}{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=233}}{{sfn|Tillman|1995|p=62}} All of the elements of the Home Fleet dispatched for Operation Leader returned to Scapa Flow by 6 October.{{sfn|Roskill|1960|p=102}}

Wartime Allied military commanders and post-war historians deemed Operation Leader a success. Rear Admiral Hustvedt believed that the best result of the attack was that it demonstrated that American and British ships could work together with "effectiveness, mutual understanding and complete cooperation". Admiral [[Patrick N. L. Bellinger]], the air commander of the US Navy's [[United States Fleet Forces Command|Atlantic Fleet]], was also pleased with the performance of the aircrews.{{sfn|Morison|2001|p=233}} Captain [[Gordon Rowe (naval officer)|Gordon Rowe]], commanding officer of ''Ranger'', did however point out that the Dauntless and Wildcat aircraft employed in the operation were outdated and that the US Navy  "...should not ask our pilots to fight in obsolete aircraft when better types are available...".{{sfn|Melien|2002|p=34}} Following the operation the commander of the Southern Attack Group, Commander J. A. Ruddy, was decorated with the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], while other servicemen taking part in the operation were awarded the [[Air Medal]] and the [[Purple Heart]].{{sfn|Thomas|2010|p=31}} The British official historian [[Stephen Roskill]] judged that the attack was an "outstanding success", especially as it was the first combat mission for sixty percent of the aircrews involved.{{sfn|Roskill|1960|p=102}}

Writing in 2012, historian Robert C. Stern stated that it is difficult to determine how many ships were sunk during Operation Leader as some of the vessels which were run ashore were possibly refloated and repaired. He assessed that five ships (''Cap Guir'', ''La Plata'', ''Rabat'', ''Skramstad'' and ''Vaagan'') were probably destroyed, with these vessels having a total of approximately 19,000 [[gross register tonnage]] of carrying capacity.{{Sfn|Stern|2012|p=195}} In contrast, Norwegian sources pre-dating Stern's claims by decades state that two ships (''Rabat'' and ''Vaagan'') were sunk,{{sfn|Hafsten|Larsstuvold|Olsen|Stenersen|2005|p=198}} and three ships (''La Plata'', ''Skramstad'' and ''Topeka'') were damaged beyond repair.{{sfn|Christensen|1988|pp=138–139}}{{sfn|Nordanger|1975|p=86}}{{sfn|Lillegaard|1986|p=123}} The German naval historian [[Jürgen Rohwer]] also lists the ships destroyed by aircraft in Operation Leader as ''La Plata'', ''Rabat'', ''Skramstad'', ''Topeka'', and ''Vaagan''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rohwer |first1=Jürgen |last2=Hümmelchen |first2=Gerhard |authorlink1=Jürgen Rohwer |authorlink2=Gerhard Hümmelchen |title=Verluste Deutscher Handelsschiffe 1939-1945 und unter deutscher Flagge fahrender ausländischer Schiffe: 1943 |trans-title=Losses of German merchant ships 1939-1945 and foreign ships sailing under German flag: 1943 |url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/verluste/ausl%2Bdtsch-4312.htm |website=Chronik des Seekrieges 1939–1945 |publisher=Württembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |accessdate=14 September 2016|date=2007 |language=German}}</ref> ''Cap Guir'', assessed by Stern as probably destroyed, is listed by Rohwer as having survived the damage inflicted by the American aircraft at Bodø. The ship was eventually sunk by Soviet torpedo bombers [[Operation Hannibal|in the Baltic]] in April 1945.<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=1148927 |shipname=Cap Guir |accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rohwer |first1=Jürgen |last2=Hümmelchen |first2=Gerhard |title=Operation "Hannibal": Die verlustreichsten Schiffsuntergänge bei der Evakuierung von Flüchtlingen und Soldaten über die Ostsee |trans-title=Operation "Hannibal": The ship losses with the highest number of casualties during the evacuation of refugees and soldiers across the Baltic Sea |url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/ksp/ostsee/schiffe.htm |website=Chronik des Seekrieges 1939–1945 |publisher=[[Württembergische Landesbibliothek|Württembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart]]|accessdate=7 June 2016|date=2007 |language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rohwer |first1=Jürgen |last2=Hümmelchen |first2=Gerhard |title=Seekrieg 1945, April |trans-title=Naval War 1945, April |url=http://www.wlb-stuttgart.de/seekrieg/45-04.htm |website=Chronik des Seekrieges 1939–1945 |publisher=Württembergische Landesbibliothek Stuttgart |accessdate=14 September 2016|date=2007 |language=German}}</ref> In his 1974 book ''Deutschlands Handelsschiffe 1939–1945'', the German maritime historian {{Interlanguage link multi|Karl-Heinz Schwadtke|de}} gives the same list as Rohwer for German ships destroyed in Operation Leader. Schwadtke states that ''La Plata'' and ''Rabat'' were the German vessels lost off the Bodø area on 4 October 1943,{{Sfn|Schwadtke|1974|pp=42–43, 72–73}} and lists ''Cap Guir'' as sunk in 1945.{{Sfn|Schwadtke|1974|pp=50–51}}

While German and Norwegian sources mostly give the same number and names of ships destroyed in Operation Leader, English-language authors are more split in their estimates. While writers like British aviation author Christopher Chant,{{sfn|Chant|2013|p=112}} American military historian [[Eric M. Hammel]],{{sfn|Hammel|2010|p=193}} American historian [[James P. Levy]],{{sfn|Levy|2003|p=138}} British military historian Chris Mann,{{sfn|Mann|2012|p=33}} and American aviation author [[Barrett Tillman]],{{sfn|Tillmann|2010|p=80}} list five ships as destroyed, others like American military historians Kermit Bonner{{sfn|Bonner|1996|p=16}} and [[Spencer C. Tucker]]{{sfn|Tucker|2012|p=1599}} write that six ships were sunk.

Stern has also written that the disruption to the convoys off Norway caused by Operation Leader would have caused even greater damage to the German war effort than the shipping losses.{{Sfn|Stern|2012|p=195}} This is in line with a wartime assessment by the British [[Ministry of Economic Warfare]], which estimated that the raid was the main factor responsible for a 58 percent decrease in the amount of [[Swedish iron-ore mining during World War II|iron ore]] shipped from the important northern Norwegian port of [[Narvik]] during October 1943.{{sfn|Hinsley|1984|p=282}}

Operation Leader was both the only offensive operation undertaken by the US Navy in northern European waters during World War II, and the last major American operation in this theatre of the war.{{sfn|Faulkner|2012|p=198}}{{sfn|Brown|2009|p=23}} ''Ranger'' remained with the Home Fleet until being replaced by British aircraft carriers in late November 1943, during which time she took part in a patrol of the Norwegian Sea. The carrier departed Scapa Flow on 26 November, and arrived in [[Boston]] on 6 December. ''Ranger'' was used to train aircrews and transport aircraft for the remainder of the war, and did not see combat again.<ref name="Ranger DANFS">{{cite web|title=Ranger IX (CV-4)|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/r/ranger-ix.html|website=[[Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships]]|publisher=Naval History and Heritage Command|accessdate=12 May 2016|date=16 September 2005}}</ref>{{sfn|Faulkner|2012|p=198}}

The German forces in Norway were taken by surprise during Operation Leader. The area had not been raided by carrier-borne aircraft for two years, leading to inadequate preparations for such an attack. Precautions against further raids were put in place, and the British carrier forces which repeatedly attacked Norway until the end of the war did not encounter any concentrations of shipping like that located by ''Ranger''{{'}}s airmen off Bodø.{{sfn|Brown|2009|p=23}} Operation Leader revealed a serious weakness in the composition of the German armed forces in occupied Norway, which were lacking sufficient numbers of combat aircraft to respond effectively to Allied attacks.{{sfn|Melien|2002|p=34}} Following the attack, the Germans searched the area for radio transmitters, arresting several local Norwegians and narrowly missing the agents of the "Pisces" group. The two members of the "Pisces" team were evacuated to the United Kingdom by [[Consolidated PBY Catalina]] [[flying boat]] on 24 November 1943.{{sfn|Ulstein|1990|p=266}} The last SIS agents of the "Crux" group were evacuated from Renga by a [[No. 330 Squadron RAF]] Catalina on 6 June 1944, but the transmitter on the island continued sending reports to the United Kingdom for the duration of the war, manned by a local volunteer who had been trained by the agents.{{sfn|Christensen|1988|pp=202–203}}{{sfn|Rørholt|Thorsen|1990|p=447}}

The wreck of the Avenger torpedo bomber shot down in the operation was located off Fagervika with the help of local Norwegians in 1987,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airgroup4.com/book/indx/index1.htm |title=1. Operation Leader: Initiation Over Norway |last=Thomas |first=Gerald W. |authorlink=Gerald W. Thomas |date= |website=Air Group 4 - "Casablanca to Tokyo" |publisher= |access-date=29 August 2016 |quote=}}</ref> and partially salvaged by the [[Royal Norwegian Navy]].{{sfn|Brødreskift|2009|p=29}}<ref name=return>{{cite web |url=http://www.airgroup4.com/norway2.htm |title=USS Ranger Veterans Return to Norway |last=Thomas |first=Gerald W. |authorlink= |date= |website=Air Group 4 - "Casablanca to Tokyo" |publisher= |access-date=29 August 2016 |quote=}}</ref> The remains of two of the airmen killed in the operation were recovered from the sea.{{sfn|Thomas|2010|p=Acknowledgements}} A memorial in the honour of the airmen killed in the operation was erected at the former site of a German coastal artillery position at Fagervika.{{sfn|Berntsen|Hauglid|1995|pp=9–10}} The memorial was dedicated on 4 October 1987 in the presence of American diplomat [[Richard Norland]], [[naval attaché]] Lieutenant Commander [[Robert B. Murrett]], and relatives of one of the airmen killed in Operation Leader.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airgroup4.com/book/c1p6.htm |title=Dedication of a monument to those lost in Operation Leader Fagervika, Norway, October 4, 1987 |last=Thomas |first=Gerald W. |authorlink= |date= |website=Air Group 4 - "Casablanca to Tokyo" |publisher= |access-date=29 August 2016 |quote=}}</ref> Included in the memorial is one of the three [[Propeller (aeronautics)|propeller]] blades recovered from the Avenger wreck, the other two blades being displayed at the [[National Naval Aviation Museum]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]] and at the [[Home Guard (Norway)|Norwegian Home Guard]] base in [[Søvik, Nordland|Søvik]], near Sandnessjøen, respectively.<ref name=return/> The memorial at Fagervika has been used as the site of remembrance ceremonies organized by the [[Norwegian Reserve Officers' Federation]] and with the participation of American veterans of Operation Leader.<ref>{{cite news |last=Krokstrand |first=Mats |date=5 July 2013 |title=Minnet falne kamerater |trans-title=Commemorated fallen comrades |url=http://www.helg.no/lokale-nyheter/minnet-falne-kamerater/s/1-63-6745068 |newspaper=Helgelendingen |location=Mosjøen |access-date=29 August 2016 |language=Norwegian }}</ref>

One of the two Douglas SBD Dauntless dive bombers shot down in the operation was located in 1990 and partially salvaged in 1993, with its engine put on display at the [[Norwegian Aviation Museum]] in Bodø.<ref name=return/> The remains of the Dauntless' two crew members were recovered from the wreck and identified at the [[Nordland Hospital|Nordland Central Hospital]] in Bodø.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airgroup4.com/mia-pow.htm |title=Airmen Missing in Action (MIAs) and Prisoners of War (POWs) from Air Group 4 |last=Thomas |first=Gerald W. |authorlink= |date= |website=Air Group 4 - "Casablanca to Tokyo" |publisher= |access-date=29 August 2016 |quote=}}</ref> The 50th anniversary of Operation Leader on 4 October 1993 was commemorated in Norway by the issuing of a [[First day of issue|first-day cover]] and the unveiling of a sculpture at [[Bodø Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airgroup4.com/norway.htm |title=Norway: A Grateful Nation Remembers |last=Thomas |first=Gerald W. |authorlink= |date= |website=Air Group 4 - "Casablanca to Tokyo" |publisher= |access-date=29 August 2016 |quote=}}</ref>

